PARAGRAPH.#text: Moody's Investors Service downgraded Bemis Co.'s BMS rating, saying the food and beverage packaging firm's credit metrics haven't shown enough improvement. The company's investment-grade rating was lowered to Baa2 from Baa1, placing it two notches above junk territory. Although the company has undertaken restructuring efforts, Moody's said, Bemis will likely continue facing challenges amid the soft economy. However, the company's outlook was changed to stable from negative, as Moody's said it expects Bemis will execute its cost-cutting initiatives and new product rollouts, helping it maintain credit metrics that are in-line with its new rating.

Headlines.Author: Kate Gibson
Headlines.Headline: MARKET SNAPSHOT: U.S. Stock Market's Climb Tied To Dollar's Fall

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Kate Gibson The U.S. stock market is paying more attention than usual to the movements of the U.S. dollar, with the greenback's newfound status as a funding currency leaving its moves highly correlated to equities and other riskier assets. Since the S&P 500 (SPX) hit a low in early March, the index of large-cap stocks has jumped nearly 60%. The U.S. dollar has moved in the opposite direction, falling 15%. "We expect the relationship between the movement in the dollar and stock prices to continue for several more months until the Fed actually steps in and begins to lift short-term interest rates," said Fred Dickson, chief market strategist at Davidson Companies.

Headlines.Headline: Broderbund match estimates, but costs raise questions

#text: Broderbund Software (BROD)

shares could come under pressure Thursday after higher-than-expected costs dragged down
    results for the Novato, Calif.-based company. Excluding an acquisition-related charge,
    Broderbund earned 18 cents a share for the quarter, in line with the analyst consensus
    estimate. The maker of the popular Myst and Riven computer games also said it would take a
    $2 million charge in its third-quarter report as it revamps some of its marketing and
    development operations. Spokesman Eric Winker declined to give specifics on what changes
    would be made, but added that "all options are on the table," including layoffs.
    Andrea Williams of Volpe Brown Whelan, who had expected Broderbund to post a 20-cent
    profit, was especially troubled by disappointing sales of the company's new education
    titles and a higher level of returns for its productivity programs. "That's a red
    flag," she said. "Either there's growing competition or the products aren't just
    that good."

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Broderbund match estimates, but costs raise questions
